</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
That's not really true.  Everything has advantages and disadvantages and need to be weighed before making judgments.<br>
<br>
Wind only produces waste during construction and decomissioning.  They have a zero daily operating cost (no people required), a variable maintenance cost, and a decent construction cost.<br>
<br>
However, it does have reliability issues.  Lack of wind for an extended period of time will create problems if there is no backup.  Also, wind turbines are particularly vulnerable to severe weather conditions.  So we probably do not want to use them as a base load source.  However, they would make good peaking capacity generation.<br>
<br>
Wind has its place.  I do not believe it to be base load because I feel it needs to be available 100% of the time under any statistically significant factor.  However, it can provide extra over-capacity power for more localized areas during peaking conditions. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1348<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/31/03 10:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=159.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Senate abandons nuclear bailout</span><hr size=1> Today, the senate abandoned plans for massive loan guarentees for building a run of experimental &quot;paper&quot; reactors.<br>
<br>
Wind and other renwables, along with energy efficiency, are supported.<br>
<br>
The controversial nuclear bailout proposals will be re-considered during house/senate conference sessions.<br>
<br>
