Reuters, 08.06.03, 2:19 PM ET<br>
 <br>
By Chris Baltimore<br>
<br>
WASHINGTON, Aug 6 (Reuters) - The U.S. nuclear industry is pursuing other federal incentives after the Senate last week dropped a Republican energy bill with <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>$10 billion in loan guarantees</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to encourage new plant construction, the Nuclear Energy Institute said on Wednesday.<br>
<br>
No nuclear power plants have been built in the United States since the partial meltdown of the reactor core of the Three Mile Island plant in Pennsylvania in 1979.<br>
<br>
Senate and House negotiators will begin hammering out a compromise energy bill when Congress returns from its summer recess in September.<br>
<br>
The Senate last week voted to revive a Democratic-written energy bill that originally cleared the chamber last year. The bill does not include a Republican-backed plan to provide some $10 billion in loan guarantees for a new generation of U.S. nuclear plants, which narrowly passed the Senate in June.<br>
<br>
The Nuclear Energy Institute, which represents most nuclear plant owners, is seeking other incentives to encourage future building, President Joe Colvin told reporters.<br>
<br>
&quot;We're going to look to see what types of measures can in fact be put back&quot; into the energy bill, Colvin said. Those may include accelerated depreciation and tax breaks, he said.<br>
<br>
Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, the Republican who will lead House-Senate negotiations to finalize an energy bill, has indicated he is willing to look at other options to jump-start the nuclear power plant industry.<br>
<br>
Critics of nuclear plant loan guarantees complained that such incentives are not needed by an established industry and carry the risk of significant costs to taxpayers if an owner went broke.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Congressional Budget Office, a nonpartisan entity, said earlier this year it considered the risk of default on such a loan guarantee to be &quot;very high&quot; because a new nuclear power plant would be &quot;uneconomic to operate.&quot;</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Nuclear experts with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology said last week that a federal tax credit of up to $200 per kilowatt hour (kWh) of the construction cost was needed to encourage private investors to build nuclear power plants. The MIT report said nuclear power costs about 6.7 cents per kWh to produce, compared to a range of 3.8 cents to 5.6 cents for plants fueled by coal or natural gas.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
Meanwhile, Entergy Corp. (nyse: ETR - news - people), the nation's second- largest operator of nuclear power plants behind Exelon Corp. (nyse: ETR - news - people), in June said it will seek regulatory approval to build a new reactor at an existing plant site in Mississippi.<br>
<br>
If approved by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, the permit could open the door for the first nuclear plant to be built in the United States in nearly a quarter of a century.<br>
<br>
{Note from Yale - This is not quite correct. Entergy IS NOT seeking approval to build a new reactor. They are only seeking an &quot;Early Site Approval&quot; which the Bush Admin is offering to pay half the cost of. It only is a ruling that nothing disqualifies the site from future construction for up to 40 years.<br>
<br>
This is what Enetrgy says: <br>
--- &quot;Entergy Will Prepare Early Site Permit at Grand Gulf Nuclear Station <br>
   <br>
Jackson, Miss. - Entergy Nuclear will prepare an application for an early site permit at the Grand Gulf Nuclear Station site in Port Gibson, Miss., to keep the option open for a new advanced reactor at sometime in the future.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><br>
&quot;We have not made a decision to start building a new nuclear unit,&quot;</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> said Randy Hutchinson, senior vice president of business development, Entergy Nuclear, a major subsidiary of Entergy. ... The early site permit process does not commit nor allow Entergy Nuclear to build a new nuclear unit. The permit only pre-approves the site for possible future construction.&quot;<br>
  End of Note)<br>
<br>
<br>
Nuclear plants generate 20 percent of U.S. electricity. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A> at: 8/7/03 11:01 pm<br></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace>NuclearSpace Message Board</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25>Energy and the Environment</a> <font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com">NuclearSpace Home Page</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.246c<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

